05085nam a22009495i 9780520967212DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20172017cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209672127 a10.1515/97805209672122doi  a(DE-B1597)519769  a(OCoLC)994006263  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aRD119b.J37 2018 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a617.9509812231 aJarrín, Alvaro, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Biopolitics of Beauty :bCosmetic Citizenship and Affective Capital in Brazil /cAlvaro Jarrín. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. The Biopolitical and Affective Dimensions of Beauty -- tChapter 1. The Eugenesis of Beauty -- tChapter 2. Plastic Governmentality -- tChapter 3. The Circulation of Beauty -- tChapter 4. Hope, Affect, Mobility -- tChapter 5. The Raciology of Beauty -- tChapter 6. Cosmetic Citizens -- tConclusion. Thinking of Beauty Transnationally -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Biopolitics of Beauty examines how beauty became an aim of national health in Brazil. Using ethnographic fieldwork carried out in Brazilian hospitals, the author shows how plastic surgeons and patients navigate the public health system to transform beauty into a basic health right. The book historically traces the national concern with beauty to Brazilian eugenics, which established beauty as an index of the nation’s racial improvement. From here, Jarrín explains how plastic surgeons became the main proponents of a raciology of beauty, using it to gain the backing of the Brazilian state. Beauty can be understood as an immaterial form of value that Jarrín calls “affective capital,” which maps onto and intensifies the social hierarchies of Brazilian society. Patients experience beauty as central to national belonging and to gendered aspirations of upward mobility, and they become entangled in biopolitical rationalities that complicate their ability to consent to the risks of surgery. The Biopolitics of Beauty explores not only the biopolitical regime that made beauty a desirable national project, but also the subtle ways in which beauty is laden with affective value within everyday social practices—thus becoming the terrain upon which race, class, and gender hierarchies are reproduced and contested in Brazil.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aBeauty, PersonalxSocial aspectszBrazil. 0aBiopoliticszBrazil. 0aPlastic surgeonsxSocial aspectszBrazil. 0aPublic healthxSocial aspectszBrazil. 0aSurgery, PlasticxSocial aspectszBrazil. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aanthropologist.  aanthropology.  abeauty culture.  abeauty standards.  abeauty.  abrazil.  abrazilian culture.  abrazilian.  acentral america.  aclass issues.  aethnographic.  aethnography.  aeugenics.  afieldwork.  ahealth and wellness.  ahealthcare rights.  ahealthcare system.  ahospital.  amedical patients.  aphysical appearance.  aplastic surgeons.  aplastic surgery.  apublic health.  arace issues.  arace.  aracism.  asocial hierarchy.  asocial studies.  asouth america.  asurgery.  aupward mobility.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052029388540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520967212?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520967212423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520967212/original